<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Lupinus chamissonis </i>is a medium-sized shrub well adapted to open, sandy environments. Its symbiotic relationship with root bacteria enables it to fix nitrogen in the soil, enabling the plants to survive in nutrient-depleted or infertile sands. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Ericameria ericoides </i>is a mounded shrub branching from a compact base. Plants produce an abundance of small, viable, plumed seeds. Seeds are easily dispersed, even long distances by wind. Seedling establishment occurs in years when soil moisture allows sufficient root development. The name <i>Haplopappus ericoides </i>is used in the older literature. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance occurs as isolated patches along California coastlines. It shares species with the <i>Abronia latifolia</i>- <i>Ambrosia chamissonis </i>and other coastal bluff scrub alliances. Stands tend to occupy more exposed settings on stabilized dunes and near-shore uplifted terraces compared to other coastal shrubby alliances such as <i>Lupinus arboreus </i>or <i>Baccharis pilularis</i>. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
