    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Af, Ah-l). Stands dominated by <i>Ericameria ericoides</i> occur generally along the coast (Pickart and Barbour 2007). Stands at Salinas River State Beach (Bluestone 1981) and at Vandenberg Air Base (Barbour and Johnson 1977) are mixed with several other species.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ag-k). Stands range north to Mendocino Co.; they have been described at Point Reyes National Seashore (Holton and Johnson 1979, Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a). They are rarely mixed, instead either <i>Ericameria ericoides</i> or <i>Lupinus chamissonis</i> dominates. Some stands have high cover of <i>Ambrosia chamissonis</i> or <i>Artemisia pycnocephala.</i> The presence of non-native annual grasses in some stands suggests increased nutrient status from nitrogen-fixing bacteria of <i>Lupinus</i> spp. (Pickart and Sawyer 1998).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-b, Bd, Bf-g). Stands exist at Nipomo Dunes in San Luis Obispo Co. and they occur farther south to Ventura and Los Angeles Cos. on sandy bluffs and dunes. Stands with <i>E. ericoides</i> and <i>Coreopsis gigantea</i> in the Point Dume area of the Santa Monica Mountains are members of the <i>Coreopsis gigantea</i> alliance (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ammophila arenaria </i>and <i>Carpobrotus edulis </i>displace species in this alliance and change environmental conditions if not controlled in this alliance. Pickart and Sawyer (1998) review methods of control. </div>
</div>

    

    

